	id="Qz_DeterminantMultilinear">
	<texsupport href="../LinearAlgebraTeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	<title>Quiz on the Multilinearity Property of Determinants</title>
	
	
	<quiz>
		<question>
			<para>Among the determinant expressions below which two are equal? With</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>
					<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{U} = \left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
6 & 4 & -2 \\
2 & 8 & 12 \\
4 & 6 & -4
\end{array}
\right] \qquad
\Mtrx{V} = 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 2 & -1 \\
1 & 4 & 6 \\
2 & 3 & -2
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
				</latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>a) &nbsp; <latex>\det(\Mtrx{U})</latex>, &nbsp; b) &nbsp; <latex>2\cdot \det(\Mtrx{V})</latex>, &nbsp; c) &nbsp; <latex>8\cdot \det(\Mtrx{V})</latex></para>
		</question>
		
		<choice>
			<answer><para>a) and (b)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Sorry! No. &ndash; While it is true that for matrices <latex>\Mtrx{U}=2\cdot \Mtrx{V}</latex>, the two determinant expressions are not equal. To solve this problem correctly, please review what the multilinearity property of determinants really means.</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>a) and c)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Correct!</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>b) and c)</para></answer>
			<info><para>No! &ndash; If you really think b) and c) are equal, with which reasoning do you deduce this from the multilinearity property of the determinant operation?</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>No two of the given determinant expressions are equal.</para></answer>
			<info><para>No! &ndash; Please review the concept of multilinearity of the determinant operation.</para></info>
		</choice>
	</quiz>
	
	<quiz>
		<question>
			<para>Which of the determinant expressions below are equal?</para>
			<ol type="a">
				<li>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
3 & 7 & 1 & 5 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 15 \\
4 & 0 & 2 & -5 \\
-4 & 0 & 0 & 10
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</li>
				<li>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
3 & 7 & 1 & 5 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 15 \\
0 & 0 & 2 & -5 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & 10
\end{array}
\right]\ +\ \det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
0 & 7 & 1 & 5 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 15 \\
4 & 0 & 2 & -5 \\
-4 & 0 & 0 & 10
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</li>
				<li>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
3 & 7 & 1 & 5 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 15 \\
0 & 0 & 2 & -5 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & 10
\end{array}
\right]\ +\ \det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0  \\
4 & 0 & 0 & 0 \\
-4 & 0 & 0 & 0
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</li>
				<li>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
3 & 7 & 1 & 5 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 15 \\
0 & 0 & 2 & -5 \\
0 & 0 & 0 & 10
\end{array}
\right]\ +\ 20\cdot \det\, 
\left[
\begin{array}{rrrr}
0 & 7 & 1 & 1 \\
0 & 1 & 6 & 3 \\
1 & 0 & 2 & -1 \\
-1 & 0 & 0 & 2
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
				</li>
			</ol>
			
		</question>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>a) and b)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Yes! This is correct: Apply linearity in the first column to express the determinant in a) as the sum of the two determinants in b).</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>a) and c)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Sorry, no! &ndash; The matrix in a) is equal to the sum of the two matrices in c). However, the determinants in a) and c) are not equal.</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>b) and d)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Yes! &ndash; Start with the determinant expression in b). In the second determinant pull a factor of <latex>4</latex> out of the first column and then a factor of <latex>5</latex> out of the fourth column. This gives the second determinant in d).</para></info>
		</choice>
		<choice>
			<answer><para>a) and b) and d)</para></answer>
			<info><para>Yes! This is correct.</para></info>
		</choice>
	</quiz>	
</quiz.pack>